<gmap_id>0x80dc0718703f68b7:0x160a3d16d30d7df4<//gmap_id><username>Naina Kurup<//username>< review>
I rented a unit at the Golden Triangle Sorrento valley facility from June-November this year, and when I got movers to get my stuff out of the unit, they found that my boxes had been chewed up, and there were rodent droppings everywhere. It was pretty ghastly to say the least, not to mention the considerable damage to a number of my personal belongings. There was a window left open next to my unit, and holes in the air vent above, which is probably how the critter got access. I had the insurance cover on the unit offered by the facility, but apparently rodent damage is exempt. I filed an incident report with the manager, who claimed action will be taken by people higher up in the food chain, but its been radio silence for more than two weeks now. Needless to say, a very unpleasant experience overall.</review>

< text>
Shaks is a family owned and family run restaurant. You can taste the influences of the countries the family hail from in their generously portioned meals. You feel like you are eating at a relatives home more than a restaurant in downtown Vista. Friendly staff, amazing food. Eat outside on the patio or have doordash,grubhub, or other delivery services to pick it up for you. They have heaters for those cooler evenings while you eat. The food may take a bit longer to get to you but know this is because they are running meals out the doors in droves! The quality of the food is superb. Highly recommend. You wont be disappointed.</text>

<review>I got the chicken kabob pita with fries, my boyfriend got a pita with lamb and a side of rice, for reference.
The chicken, pita, and lamb were great. Flavorful and tender.
The rice and fries were extremely bland.
My pita came with a "garlic" sauce. There was a side of what I assumed was supposed to garlic sauce for my fries as well. But it was extremely grainy, way strong, and frankly spicy. I saw a review that said the horseradish side was a great surprise. It's not a horseradish that me or my boyfriend have ever had, unless it tastes strong of garlic as well. My pita seemed to have the same substance on it, so I'm assuming it's garlic sauce, but who knows. It made eating the pita pretty impossible, I ended up picking around it.
This is obviously a personal opinion, but wanted to share if anyone could use the advice on what to order!<//review>< pics>
None< /pics>

<review>Though it has only officially been around since 2018, Shaks Mediterranean Bistro traces its roots back nearly three decades, to when it was known as the Armenian Caf√© in Carlsbad.

Shaks is located on Main Street in Vista and is most well-known for its traditional Middle Eastern cuisine, family-friendly atmosphere, and all-around good value.

Perennial menu favorites include hummus, shawarma, falafel, kabobs, and fresh salads.

Previous guests of Middle Eastern descent have noted that the food was about as authentic as you‚Äôre likely to get, and that the portion sizes were so hefty there were often leftovers.</review><rating>4<//rating><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMCFNCIOeDj4HhtTimpJlNqbdA8rcv3XGgEe23z=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics><username>Ankit Patel</username><time>1598791254351<//time></record></dataset><record>

<review>My wife & I recently visited San Diego County and dined at Shaks on three occasions, twice for weekend brunch and once for lunch. Former Carlsbad residents, we often dined at Shak's predecessor, the Armenian Cafe. Father Eddie and sons source the finest authentic Mediterranean meats, cheeses, olives and produce. The weekend brunch offers delicious omelettes with wonderful combinations of these ingredients plus the tastiest potatoes to be found. Shak's lemon-soup, pita, rice, and tabbouleh compliment main dishes such as chicken kabobs, giro, and lamb. Shaks also offers party-room accommodations that work well for family or business events. We highly recommend this fabulous family restaurant where you'll feel like part of the family!<//review></record></dataset><record>

< text>
Two of us arrived early on a Sat. evening.  Was told the wait would be about 10 min.  As three groups of 4 people, who came in after us, were seated, we approached the host only to be told he had already crossed our name off the list in error...about 40 minutes have passed by this point.  After being seated, we waited another 20 minutes for a waiter to approach and then we were told we couldn't order our food yet, as the kitchen needs time to catch up.üòü  We did order our drinks and eventually they were brought and we could order some food.  We ordered an an appetizer of Saganaki, which should be lit on fire momentarily at the table, but the waitress said she couldn't do tonight.  Moments later, the same waitress brought some Saganaki to an adjacent table and lit it right up!  The rest of our meal was quite good, but after spending almost 3 hours there and dealing with the poor service I have my reservations about the place.  Training of your wait staff shouldn't be done on a busy Sat. night.  Don't go there on a weekend.  They need to be mindful of the fact that bad service will reflect in their return business and yes, they just opened, but they have been in business for many years at another location and should have known better.< /text>

I'm a Vista native that's been transplanted in the PNW and I've yet to find Mediterranean food as delicious as what Shaks serves up. Whenever I'm in town I have to stop in. It's not an option. I must eat at Shaks.

<Review>Let's face it: If you're going to the DPSS Office, you've got some issues. So does everyone else there. Which makes for a lot of cranky people on both sides of the windows. I found the staff at this office to be attentive and helpful once they knew what I needed.  That was the key.  If you show up and expect the System to roll out the welcome mat and anticipate your needs, well I think you are bound to be disappointed and frustrated. If you ask for help, my experience tells me you will get it promptly. There are at least 2 roaming staff in each large waiting area to help you if you are confused or don't know what forms you need or...well, any of the myriad of hurdles that face those needing assistance. If you are homeless do yourself a favor and visit the Long Beach Multi-Purpose Center just off of Anaheim and Harbor on 12th Street. That site has a DPSS worker available Mon-Wed-Fri (as of this posting 04-26-2016). This worker can screen you, provide you with the paperwork you will need and actually make an appointment for you with the office on Santa Fe Ave. This can save you a whole lot of time and bus tokens.<//Review>< Gmap_id>
